-- 
U.K. Stocks Fall the Most in Two Years; 11% Decline on Feb. High

-- B y   B e n   E d w a r d s
-- 
2011-08-04T16:18:25Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-03/lloyds-aviva-rio-tinto-unilever-u-k-irish-equity-preview.html
U.K. stocks fell the most in more
than two years, extending the benchmark  FTSE 100 Index (UKX) ’s decline
from this year’s high to 11 percent, amid concern that the
global economic recovery is stalling.  Rio Tinto  Group, the world’s second-largest mining company,
lost 5.4 percent as earnings missed estimates.  Inmarsat Plc (ISAT) 
slumped 19 percent after the satellite-services company cut its
growth forecast.  Randgold Resources Ltd. (RRS)  surged 6.6 percent
after earnings tripled.  The FTSE 100 tumbled 191.37, or 3.4 percent, to 5,393.14 at
the 4:30 p.m. close in London, for the gauge’s fifth day of
losses and its largest slump since March 2009. The FTSE All-
Share Index slid 3.5 percent today, while Ireland’s ISEQ Index
dropped 3.6 percent.  “The underlying issues aren’t really any different than
they were 24 hours ago,” said  Michael Hewson , a market analyst
at CMC Markets in  London . “There are still fears about this
week’s payroll figures. Unless we get a very good number, I
can’t see when the current weakness in the stock market is going
to change.”  The Labor Department’s monthly payrolls report, released
tomorrow, may show U.S. employers added 85,000 workers in July,
according to the median forecast in a Bloomberg survey of
economists.  The  Bank of England  held its benchmark  interest rate  at a
record low of 0.5 percent today, as forecast by all 55
economists surveyed by Bloomberg News.  Rio Tinto Drops  Rio Tinto sank 5.4 percent to 3,796.5 pence. The company
reported first-half underlying profit of $7.8 billion, trailing
the $8.3 billion mean estimate of nine analysts compiled by
Bloomberg.  BHP Billiton Ltd. (BHP) , the world’s largest mining company,
dropped 5.1 percent to 2,013 pence. That’s a ninth day of losses
and the longest losing streak on record.  Xstrata Plc (XTA) , the
biggest exporter of power-station coal, slumped 8.5 percent to
1,085 pence, its biggest slide since October 2009.  Vedanta Resources Plc tumbled 9.4 percent to 1,486 pence,
its largest decline since March 2009. Eurasian Natural Resources
Corp. dropped 8 percent to 663 pence, its biggest retreat since
May 2010.  Inmarsat plummeted 19 percent to 394.5 pence, the largest
retreat since its initial public offering in 2005, as the
London-based company cut its growth forecast for its mobile
satellite services business.  Lloyds, RBS, Barclays  Banking stocks also retreated, led by  Lloyds Banking Group
Plc. (LLOY)  Britain’s biggest mortgage provider declined 10 percent to
35 pence after posting a first-half net loss of 2.3 billion
pounds ($3.8 billion), wider than analysts had predicted. That’s
the bank’s biggest drop since May 2009.  Royal Bank of Scotland Plc, the U.K.’s biggest government-
controlled bank, slid 6.1 percent to 30.3 pence.  Barclays Plc (BARC) 
plummeted 7.8 percent to 196 pence, its largest tumble since
February 2010.  Royal Dutch Shell Plc (RDSA) ,  Europe ’s largest oil company, fell
5.2 percent to 2,003 pence as crude dropped to a five-week low
in  New York . Separately, the company said its Nigerian joint
venture will pay compensation for two oil spills in 2008 in the
country’s  Niger Delta .  Misys Plc (MSY) , a U.K. software provider for the financial and
health-care industries, plunged 19 percent to 291.3 pence after
Fidelity National Information Services Inc. said it was no
longer considering a takeover offer for the company. That’s the
London-based company’s biggest decline since 2003.  Randgold Resources Ltd., a miner of the metal in west
Africa, surged 6.6 percent to 5,920 pence as second-quarter net
income tripled to $113.3 million.  Unilever, the world’s second-largest maker of consumer
products, jumped 2.7 percent to 1,957 pence after reporting
first-half net income of 2.2 billion euros ($3.1 billion),
beating the average analyst estimate of 2.06 billion euros.  To contact the reporter on this story:
